'''Minicharged particles''' (or '''milli-charged particles''') are a proposed type of subatomic particle. They are charged, but with a tiny fraction of the [[charge of the electron]]. They weakly interact with matter. Minicharged particles are not part of the [[Standard Model]]. One proposal to detect them involved photons tunneling through an opaque barrier in the presence of a perpendicular magnetic field, the rationale being that a pair of oppositely charged minicharged particles are produced that curve in opposite directions, and recombine on the other side of the barrier reproducing the photon again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phys.org/news/2012-10-tunneling-kind-physics.html|title=Tunneling of the third kind' experiment could search for new physics|last=Zyga|first=Lisa|date=3 October 2012|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref>
Minicharged particles would result in vacuum magnetic [[dichroism]],<ref name="Ringwald">{{cite journal|arxiv=hep-ph/0607118|title=Polarized Light Propagating in a Magnetic Field as a Probe of Millicharged Fermions|last=Ringwald|first=Andreas|author2=Holger Gies |author3=Joerg Jaeckel |date=11 July 2006|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.97.140402|volume=97|journal=Physical Review Letters|pmid=17155223|page=140402|bibcode=2006PhRvL..97n0402G}}</ref> and would cause energy loss in [[microwave cavity|microwave cavities]].<ref name="Ringwald2">{{cite journal|arxiv=hep-ph/0608238|title=Accelerator Cavities as a Probe of Millicharged Particles|last=Ringwald|first=Andreas|author2=H. Gies |author3=J. Jaeckel |date=21 Aug 2006|work=|doi=10.1209/epl/i2006-10356-5|volume=76|journal=Europhysics Letters (EPL)|pages=794–800|bibcode=2006EL.....76..794G}}</ref> Photons from the [[cosmic microwave background]] would be dissipated by galactic-scale magnetic fields if minicharged particles existed, so this effect could be observable.<ref name="Burrage">{{cite journal|arxiv=0909.0649|title=[0909.0649] Late time CMB anisotropies constrain mini-charged particles|last=Burrage|first=Clare|author2=J. Jaeckel |author3=J. Redondo |author4=A. Ringwald |date=3 Sep 2009|work= |doi=10.1088/1475-7516/2009/11/002 |volume=2009 |journal=Journal of Cosmology and Astroparticle Physics |page=002|bibcode=2009JCAP...11..002B}}</ref> In fact the dimming observed of remote supernovae that was used to support [[dark energy]] could also be explained by the formation of minicharged particles.<ref name="Ahlers">{{cite journal|arxiv=0904.0998|title=[0904.0998] The Hubble diagram as a probe of mini-charged particles|last=Ahlers|first=Markus|date=7 April 2009|work=|doi=10.1103/PhysRevD.80.023513|volume=80|journal=Physical Review D|bibcode=2009PhRvD..80b3513A}}</ref>
Tests of Coulomb's law can be applied to set bounds on minicharged particles.
